I’ve visited the first Ajo y Oregano near Parkchester. This new location is beautiful. Tucked in Belmont, Bronx just around the corner of Little Italy. This food is delicious. The presentation is beautiful and the owners intent was to make you feel as if you were in the campos de la Republica Dominicana. Establishment doesn’t have a liquor license which would have been nice to have sangria or a glass of wine with my meal. The establishment adhered to covid-19 restrictions and ensured everyone ate safely indoors while maintaining social distance. I hope they do expand their menu and add more of the incredible cuisines from the Dominican Republic.

Great and tasteful Dominican food, I think is one of the best and authentic I’ve ever tried in NY. This place wants to show to their guests some Dominican culture, traditions from the country like the flamboyant trees painted on the lids of the tiny pans they serve the food, the pans themselves that are use to cook in the DR and the restaurant is decorated that way, very colorful, the oil paintings, the aluminum jarros (mugs) where they serve the juices, the pilones where they serve the mofongo, etc, etc... Even in the restrooms, they used a pan as a vessel sink lol! What a clever idea! The bog rolls are placed with a mini wooden hammer and a written joke, telling you “break the glass, in case of emergency” because there’s a dried corn cob behind a piece of glass LMAO!!! There’s so many details everywhere that you just have to smile and enjoy them!  Be ready to wait, because it’s always crowded and the food can take a little longer than other places to arrive to your table, but it’s worthy if you want to eat great and authentic Dominican dishes.  Highly recommended if you want to try this type of food and learn some Dominican traditions.
